aborer’, which suggests that <i>leche</i> could refer to an amateur ‘medicine man’ who supplied folk remedies."]},{"name":"Litch","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Leitch  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":15,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":40,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When William Leitch was born in 1275, in Chatsworth, Derbyshire, England, his father, John Leche - Esquire of Eggemere and Wigtown, Norfolk, was 20 and his mother, Cecilla de Dunbar, was 3. He had at least 1 daughter with Cecily. He died in 1320, in Paston, Norfolk, England, at the age of 45."},"et":{"1275–1320":"1275–1320","1290–1320":"1290–1320","1290–Male":"1290–Surnud","1300–1377":"1300–1377","1